<i>Saucerottia cyanura</i>
The <b>Blue-tailed Hummingbird</b> (<i>Amazilia cyanura</i>), sometimes placed in the genus <i><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saucerottia" title="Saucerottia" class="mw-redirect">Saucerottia</a></i>, is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hummingbird" title="Hummingbird">hummingbird</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trochilidae" title="Trochilidae" class="mw-redirect">Trochilidae</a> family. It is found in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Costa_Rica" title="Costa Rica">Costa Rica</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Salvador" title="El Salvador">El Salvador</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guatemala" title="Guatemala">Guatemala</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honduras" title="Honduras">Honduras</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicaragua" title="Nicaragua">Nicaragua</a>. Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitats</a> are subtropical or tropical dry <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forest" title="Forest">forests</a>, subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests, and heavily degraded former forest.
